{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487397","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487397"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:09:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:09:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"339"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"339","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/339"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.06,0.01,0.05,0.82]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"339"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113444"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"339","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/339"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"339"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95465"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"341"},{"type":"tags","id":"1519"},{"type":"tags","id":"1575"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1491"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46952"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113444","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113444"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to hospital for a semi-elective laparoscopic cholecystectomy for acute cholecystitis. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. The procedure is uncomplicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEight hours post-operatively, he appears well and is pain-free. On examination, he has dry mucous membranes and mildly decreased skin turgor. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 100/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. His urine output since the operation has been 100 mL. There is no suprapubic discomfort or palpable bladder on abdominal examination.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bladder scan","Continue current management","Intravenous furosemide","Urinary catheterisation","1L of isotonic saline over 4 hours"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has post-operative oliguria with signs of hypovolaemia. The urine output of 200 mL over 12 hours (approximately 0.24 mL/kg/hour) is significantly below the target of 0.5-1 mL/kg/hour. Clinical signs suggesting hypovolaemia include dry mucous membranes, decreased skin turgor, relative tachycardia, and borderline hypotension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E1L of isotonic saline over 4 hours\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management. Fluid resuscitation is the first-line treatment for post-operative oliguria when clinical signs suggest hypovolaemia. This controlled rate of administration allows for reassessment of fluid status and urine output response.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinue current management\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate given the concerning signs of hypovolaemia and risk of acute kidney injury if left untreated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous furosemide\u003C/strong\u003E would be contraindicated in a hypovolaemic patient as it would worsen the fluid deficit. Loop diuretics are only appropriate when there is evidence of fluid overload.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBladder scan\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eurinary catheterisation\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if urinary retention was suspected. However, the absence of suprapubic pain or a palpable bladder, combined with evidence that the patient has passed some urine, makes urinary retention unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPost-operative oliguria is common and can be due to various causes including hypovolaemia, acute kidney injury, or urinary retention. The key is to identify the underlying cause through careful clinical assessment. In this case, the clinical signs clearly point to hypovolaemia as the likely cause.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["An intravenous fluid bolus should be the first consideration for oliguria in the immediate post-operative period, aiming for urine output of 0.5-1 mL/kg/hour.","Clinical signs of dehydration include dry mucous membranes, decreased skin turgor, tachycardia, and hypotension.","Urinary retention is unlikely in the absence of suprapubic pain or a palpable bladder, even with reduced urine output."],"references":["1) Chenitz KB, Lane-Fall MB. Decreased urine output and acute kidney injury in the postanesthesia care unit. Anesthesiology clinics. 2012 Sep 1;30(3):513-26."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95465"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"339"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95465","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95465"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-12T09:30:21+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-12T09:32:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"339"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113444"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":